{"id":"2208.13856","submitter":"Dvij Kalaria","authors":"Dvij Kalaria, Qin Lin and John M. Dolan","title":"Delay-aware Robust Control for Safe Autonomous Driving and Racing","comments":"Under review at IEEE TIV","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Delays endanger safety of autonomous systems operating in a rapidly changing\nenvironment, such as nondeterministic surrounding traffic participants in\nautonomous driving and high-speed racing. Unfortunately, delays are typically\nnot considered during the conventional controller design or learning-enabled\ncontroller training phases prior to deployment in the physical world. In this\npaper, the computation delay from nonlinear optimization for motion planning\nand control, as well as other unavoidable delays caused by actuators, are\naddressed systematically and unifiedly. To deal with all these delays, in our\nframework: 1) we propose a new filtering approach with no prior knowledge of\ndynamics and disturbance distribution to adaptively and safely estimate the\ntime-variant computation delay; 2) we model actuation dynamics for steering\ndelay; 3) all the constrained optimization is realized in a robust tube model\npredictive controller. For the application merits, we demonstrate that our\napproach is suitable for both autonomous driving and autonomous racing. Our\napproach is a novel design for a standalone delay compensation controller. In\naddition, in the case that a learning-enabled controller assuming no delay\nworks as a primary controller, our approach serves as the primary controller's\nsafety guard.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Aug 2022 19:54:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-31"}
